      {
         "id": "SECTION_introduction",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "### Introduction\n\nBefore moving on, reflect and answer:",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "markdown",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 1: Discoveries</b><br /><br />Who discovered America?</div></div></center>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p>Answering challenging questions with simple answers may be tempting, but it often leads to wrong conclusions. For instance, in classrooms, students are often taught that history begins with the arrival of a single person, ignoring all prior context.</p><p>In this section, we briefly explore the concept of \"discovery\" of America (<i>Abya Yala</i>), but leave room for deeper considerations. For a more detailed analysis of different perspectives on discoveries, we recommend Stuart C. Brown’s work (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('47cfc7a1-a884-4bb4-80a8-376f8cca122b'); return false;\">Brown, Stuart C., <htdate0></a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "1993",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_word",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>The Meaning of “Discovery”</h3><p>During a conversation with Ludwing Nguillatun, a member of the Mapuche indigenous community (Wallmapu), one phrase caught my attention: “people study letters, not words.” This remark highlights the importance of understanding not only the superficial meaning of words but also their deeper nuances — thereby avoiding simplistic answers to complex questions such as the one we are discussing here.</p><p>According to the <b>Britannica Dictionary</b>, \"discover\" means (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('cefb324d-a55f-40c2-89be-1ba8f761af60'); return false;\">The Britannica Dictionary, \"discover\", <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>):</p><p><ul class=\"citation\"><li>\"1: to see, find, or become aware of (something) for the first time.\"</li></ul></p><p>The notion of \"... become aware of (something) for the first time\" can vary among different individuals, particularly in contexts where global communication channels are absent.</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2024",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  }
               ],
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_christian",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>The Iberian Discovery</h3><p>From the Iberian perspective, Christopher Columbus is commonly recognized as the discoverer of the \"New World,\" although some accounts indicate that Rodrigo de Triana may have sighted the continent first (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('9c2fe063-9428-4706-b116-ddb07176bdc3'); return false;\">Sanders, Ralph, <htdate0>, pp. 1</a>).</p><p>Several factors explain why credit was given to Columbus, but one stands out: the possibility that Rodrigo de Triana was a converted Jew (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('4a21ac3a-0e46-4806-945a-86b3377f6c57'); return false;\">Zielonka, Rabbi Martin, <htdate1></a>), which could have limited his recognition as the true discoverer.</p><p>It is also noteworthy that Iberian accounts themselves mention the presence of indigenous peoples who were already inhabiting America (<i>Abya Yala</i>) (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('a464098f-8602-46a0-8ade-ad1f034621ee'); return false;\">Hofmann, Sabine, <htdate2></a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('6bffd681-8f79-4773-914b-45fcc09bb6a2'); return false;\">Cristóbal Colon, <htdate3>, pp. 184 - 186</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('daaaf7ba-7319-463b-a30b-55b14dbbad94'); return false;\">Casas, Bartolomé de las F, <htdate4>, pp. 477</a>).</p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": [
                  {
                     "type": "gregory",
                     "year": "2021",
                     "month": "-1",
                     "day": "-1"
                  },
                  {
