               "PostMention": ""
            },
            {
               "text": "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-infinity\" style=\"font-size: 1em;\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\" style=\"background-color: #D7FFE4;\"><b>Mathematics in History</b><br /><br />When we speak about who \"discovered\" a region, we usually think of the first one, the \"number 1.\" However, upon closer examination of the accounts, we see that these individuals were rarely alone.<br /><br />European colonizers’ writings, which describe interactions with indigenous peoples, suggest that there were already other “number 1s” before them.<br /><br />Based on archaeological findings and genetic studies that demonstrate the presence of earlier peoples before the so-called discoverers, it may be more appropriate to think of groups as the true discoverers of each region, rather than isolated individuals.</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      },
      {
         "id": "SECTION_conclusion",
         "text": [
            {
               "text": "<h3>Conclusion</h3><p>The scientific conclusion may cause discomfort, as it removes the notion of absolute certainty. However, this uncertainty invites us to reflect on our need for definite answers.</p><p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Reflection 2: On Knowledge</b><br /><br />Could assuming we know everything become a barrier to new learning?<br /><br />Might the “safe” answers we accept have overlooked important facts?<br /><br />After reading this text, is your understanding of “discovery” still the same?<br /><br />Regarding the question <i>“Who discovered America (Abya Yala)?”</i>, is your perspective aligned with current scientific knowledge, or do you still feel the need to attribute the discovery to a single person?</div></div></center></p>",
               "source": null,
               "date_time": null,
               "isTable": false,
               "imgdesc": "",
               "format": "html",
               "PostMention": ""
            }
         ]
      }
